<author><name><![CDATA[psycopathicteen]]></name></author>
<updated>2014-09-16T19:03:42-07:00</updated>
<published>2014-09-16T19:03:42-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11631&amp;p=133979#p133979</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11631&amp;p=133979#p133979"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Can SNES Vram be expanded?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11631&amp;p=133979#p133979"><![CDATA[
Do this for every dynamically animated object.<br /><br />- Check if there is enough DMA time.<br />- If not, don't update animation frame<br />- If so, continue<br />- Clear object's vram slot (area it takes up in VRAM) from the vram slot table<br />- Find new vram slot, using the vram slot table<br />- If slots are different, update animation frame<br />- If slots are the same, compare new and old animation frames<br />- If animation frames are the same, don't update animation frame<br />- If animation frames are different, update animation frame<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4383">psycopathicteen</a> — Tue Sep 16, 2014 7:03 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
